<br>
For those of you who don't remember, this virus wiped out hard drives, and for some motherboards it flashed the BIOS to kill the computer completely.<br>
<br>
Tech support where I worked was backed up for hours for about a week ... and this was industry-wide.<br>
<br>
This virus had been in the wild for about a year, but virus software had only been detecting it for a couple of months ... so it affected a lot of people.<br>
<br>
So anyway, my point ... =) ... we needed to find a solution to the problem fast, and we called McAfee first, and they offered no solutions (and in fact just sent people with the virus over to our support teams without helping them).  Symantec, however, gave us a bootable floppy disk image that we could send to people that would get them up and running again, which was necessary because debugging/repartitioning/reformatting the hard drive did not remove the virus (it created it's own little partition on the hard drive and reinfected itself later).<br>
<br>
From that point forward, I've been using Norton Antivirus only.  Plus, Symantec puts out some other nice utilities that are worth supporting, such as Ghost.<br>
<br>
I think that Norton is a bit cheaper too, if that makes any difference.  =) <p><br>
