*Rubs hands together*<br>
<br>
True, if Linux was a bit more popular (or BSD, which is getting a lot of publicity now) there would be a lot more people *trying* to make viruses.  But they'd have a much, much more difficult time on their hands than trying to infect the gaping holes in Outlook or a WinXP user that, by default, has administrator-type access.  It'd be nowhere near as bad as the FUD-spreaders (mainly Microsoft) claim.<br>
A small tutorial on the short life and hard times of a Linux virus:<br>
http://librenix.com/?inode=21<br>
<br>
Anyone stupid enough to run as root would get infected badly, but even a totally clueless newb friend of mine who keeps phoning up asking how to move the mouse, knows not to run as root.<br>
<br>
Next misconception - no apps!<br>
There are loads of apps!  Maybe you just don't know where to find them.  What's missing?<br>
Here's what I needed -<br>
Office suite:  Staroffice, Applixware, Gnumeric, KWord, KOffice etc...<br>
Graphics:  GIMP (who needs Photoshop when you have this beauty, and for free too), plus several lighter alternatives...<br>
Web browsing: Mozilla (I use this even in Windows), Netscape, Konqueror, Opera, Galeon, Lynx, Links...<br>
Email: Evolution, KMail, mutt, pine, emacs<br>
News: trn, emacs, pan...<br>
Text Editing: jed, jove, joe, vi, vim, emacs, pico, nano, kate...<br>
Palm Syncing: pilot-link, syncmal (avantgo), j-pilot, kpilot, gnome-pilot...<br>
File Manager: command line, mc, gmc, konqueror, emelfm<br>
Instant Messaging: licq, jabber, gabber, etc...<br>
Multimedia: xmms, mpg123, aktion, xvidplay...<br>
IRC: BitchX, ircii, XChat...<br>
CDR burning: cdrecord, cdrdao, xcdroast, gnome-toaster, kburncd, etc etc..<br>
<br>
Didn't have to pay a penny for any of it either, and it's all open-source so if I knew C (which I don't) it'd be easy to tweak them to my needs.  If any bugs are discovered, someone will write a patch within a few hours (compared to the weeks of say, Windows Update)<br>
<br>
The only things missing are Games.  Despite popular belief, The Sims *does* get boring after a while, as do QuakeIII and xbill.  And that's where a dual-boot with Windows comes in most useful.<br>
<br>
Doesn't seem lacking in apps to me though!  And no talking paperclip to boot. <p>-- <BR>
