</font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usynergistx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>synergist x</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/5/02 9:20:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneralot.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1248.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://rcloues.home.mindspring.com/images/tiny_x.png width=80 height=80></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Anybody have a Anti-virus program they want to reccomend</span><hr size=1> Win2k isn't slow.  True, it needs more memory than Win98, but the benefits are more than worth it - it's much more stable and performs about the same--if not faster--in games and other common applications.  And my e:\winnt directory only takes up 1.15 gigabytes, not 1.8... *shrugs*<br>
<br>
Windows XP is far too bloated.  It's essentially Win2k with a candy coating - I don't see any real reason to upgrade.<br>
<br>
Tudamorf said: <i>Well, if you set up your default accounts with administrator-level access in 2k/XP, don't complain when you get what's coming to you.</i><br>
<br>
When I installed WinXPPro, it gave my account administrative priviledges without even asking.  The default login screen also hides the Administrator account, so most people won't even know that there are various levels of accounts (I didn't create any other accounts, since I'm the only person who uses my computer, so I don't know what the default level is for accounts that aren't created at install time). Most people won't care, either; if anything, they'll be glad they *don't* have to worry about logging in as the Administrator any time they want to make changes; if given the option, they probably *wouldn't* change their account priviledges to something slightly less powerful. <p><hr>
<i>All we're waiting for is for something worth waiting for...</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/6/02 1:39:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneralot.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1248.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/lag999/rtfm.txt width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Anybody have a Anti-virus program they want to reccomend</span><hr size=1> synergist x says:  <b><i>When I installed WinXPPro, it gave my account administrative priviledges without even asking.</b></i><br>
<br>
Ugh ... the more I hear about XP, the more I'm glad I didn't "side-grade" to it from 2K.  At least in 2K, there's a clear distinction between administrator access and other users, and you can very easily create a restricted user who can't mess with OS/program files or see other users' directories, or a power user who can mess with programs but not the OS.  There's even a sort of setuid bit like *nix, and it's very easy to tweak permissions on directory structures (recursively or just for one), although network access is a bit obtuse.<br>
<br>
As for slowness comment, I haven't found that to be true at all.  Win2K will play recent games and benchmarks just as fast in Direct3D as Win98SE and sometimes even faster in OpenGL, provided you are using well optimized drivers.  I've run it on PIIs with 64Mb memory, and it certainly doesn't feel slower than Win98.  The worst thing is the long boot time, but unlike 98SE, you don't need to reboot all the time.<br>
<br>
By the way the \WINNT directory on this system is 927 Mb, don't know where that 1.8 Gb figure comes from. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucloudien.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cloudien</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(1/6/02 8:56:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneralot.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1248.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.cloudk.clara.net/storage/zidane2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Anybody have a Anti-virus program they want to reccomend</span><hr size=1> Hrmm it's easy enough to differentiate between account types on WinXP once it's up and running.  It's probably even easier in fact, since it has the new "task based" control panel.  I think it's something like control panel -> manage users -> click on the user -> change account type.<br>
<br>
It's just that the default users it creates on installation are administrator types, and Joe Sixpack doesn't really know the difference, or why it's important to change it.  I think Win2K does this as well (it's just not as big a deal, since it isn't marketed towards home users)<br>
<br>
As for Win2K vs Win98, no contest :)  Win2K was the best thing to come out of Microsoft since the optical mouse... whereas Win98 was the foundation for "Millennium".  Nuff said.<br>
I never noticed a difference in performance at all, except that it takes longer to boot up.  WinXP cures that.  It uses a little more RAM, but that's no big deal these days... I'd gladly use a little extra RAM rather than going back to Win98 and suffering all the crashes and blue screens. <p>-- <BR>
